\end{array}
$$

After rearranging and simplifying, we get
$$
\begin{array}{l}
\left(y^{\prime}+z^{\prime}\right) x+\left(z^{\prime}+x^{\prime}\right) y+\left(x^{\prime}+y^{\prime}\right) z \geqslant \\
2 \sqrt{\left(y^{\prime} z^{\prime}+z^{\prime} x^{\prime}+x^{\prime} y^{\prime}\right)(y z+z x+x y)}
\end{array}
$$

By the equality condition of the Cauchy-Schwarz inequality, we know that the equality in (1) holds if and only if \( \frac{x^{\prime}}{x}=\frac{y^{\prime}}{x}=\frac{z^{\prime}}{x} \). The theorem is thus proved.

